Accessing constants in inner classes has some weird rules. "const" that is preloaded in script can not be accessed normally, but if the script is preloaded as local const of inner class it will work. It's easier to explain by using example.

Example script "testconst.gd":

``` gdscript
extends Node2D

const Class = preload("testconst.gd")
const root_const = 1

func _ready():
    print("BaseInner.base_inner_const: " + str(BaseInner.base_inner_const) + " editor not seeing")
    var base = BaseInner.new() #calls BaseInner._init()
    base.test_call()
    pass

class BaseInner:
    const base_inner_const = 2
    const ClassSurogate = preload("testconst.gd") #same as Class constant

    func _init():
        print("Base root_const: " + str(root_const) )
        #print("Base Class.root_const: " + str(Class.root_const) ) #does not work, invalid index in constatn expresion
        print("Base ClassSurogate.root_const: " + str(ClassSurogate.root_const) )
        #print("Other other_inner_const: " + str(Class.OtherInner.other_inner_const) ) #does not work
        #print("Other other_inner_const: " + str(OtherInner.other_inner_const) ) #does not work

    func test_call():
        #print( "Test call: " + str(Class.OtherInner.other_inner_const) ) #OtherInner used in constant expression
        print( "Test call: " + str(ClassSurogate.OtherInner.other_inner_const) )


class DerivedInner extends BaseInner:
    const derived_inner_const = 3

    func _init():
        print("Derived root_const: " + str(root_const) )

class OtherInner:
    const other_inner_const = 4

```

This syntax works to check an array for a given value:

if my_val in my_array:

But this syntax does not work to check if a given value is absent from an array:

if my_val not in my_array:

It would be good if the not keyword can be used in this context. Otherwise we have to do something like this:

if my_val in my_array:
  pass
else:
  # do something here

It's a workaround, but it's not as neat and seems unnecessary.

